There are a fair number of classicists here, so this will be old news to many, but the names of the Greek vowels epsilon and upsilon--"e psilon," "u psilon"--translate to "simple e,"  and "simple u." As opposed to the common digraphs/diphthongs "ei" and "ou." "O micron" and "O mega" are "little o" and "big O" respectively.
"Psilon" would, of course, be spelled with a psi.

